    "Various factors have been found to drive Bitcoin prices, such as searching sites (Kristoufek 2013), market forces (Ciaian et al. 2016a), economic fundamentals (Li and Wang 2017), transaction speed (Corbet et al. 2018a), market attention (Urquhart 2018), trading volume (Balcilar et al. 2017; Bouri et al. 2019b), economic policy uncertainty (Demir et al. 2018; Fang et al. 2019), cryptocurrency liquidity (Wei 2018), Google search index (Bleher and Dimpfl 2019; Nasir et al. 2019), and Twitter tweets (Karalevicius et al. 2018; Shen et al. 2019).",
    "In addition to price, these factors have been found to predict cryptocurrency returns, volume, and volatility.",
    "Various models and machine learning techniques, such as long-short-term memory neural networks (Alonso-Monsalve et al. 2020; Lahmiri and Bekiros 2019; McNally et al. 2018) and support vector machines (Akyildirim et al.",
    "2021), have been employed to predict cryptocurrency returns.",
    "Studies show that cryptocurrency liquidity relies on specific variables and is irrelevant to global financial market variables (Brauneis et al. 2021)."
